Look I'm all for the artists who actually HAVE the leverage using it to try to get Joe Rogan tf out of here. Especially the rich, white ones.

I'm clear that I, myself, have not the power to make any such ultimatums (nor do any of my artist friends, nor our collective audiences). It'd be like trying to boycott Amazon. So the rest of us are kind of stuck here.

And we've been stuck here since the late 00s when they gutted MySpace as an alternative music distro platform overnight and started pushing us towards these consolidated streaming platforms for next to no actual compensation.

There is no choice for most of us— tried the whole "resist Spotify" thing in 2014-2015 and all it got me was more obscurity.

10/10 What happens when the masters of culture aren’t fans of the culture? Spotify and OpenAI may democratize access, but at what cost? If we want art that matters, we must demand systems that value creators, not just consumers.

8/10 The masters of these platforms claim neutrality—they’re “just tools.” But tools shape behavior, and Spotify and OpenAI are shaping a world where creators are disposable. Who holds them accountable when the tools erase the artist?

6/10 The artist’s plight isn’t new, but now it’s industrialized. Spotify commodifies music; OpenAI commodifies imagination. When creativity becomes currency, what’s left for those who create but can’t compete?

5/10 Spotify squeezes musicians; OpenAI squeezes creators. Both extract value without truly contributing to the craft. The systems don’t respect the process—only the product. Is this the beginning of a culture without humanity?

3/10 Creators are the soul of culture, but platforms don’t see them as people—just producers of “content.” Spotify and OpenAI don’t care about the creator’s journey, only about the consumer’s click. What does this indifference mean for the future of art?

2/10 Art used to inspire revolutions; now it’s crushed under the weight of micro-pennies and playlists. Spotify doesn’t serve musicians; it serves metrics. When the system rewards volume over value, how much beauty gets lost in the noise?

1/10 The master of Spotify isn’t a music fan; the system wasn’t built for musicians but for monetizing moments. The platform doesn’t amplify artistry—it optimizes for engagement. What happens to music when the curator is an algorithm and the master is indifferent?

But Meta’s says its all about transparency and self-discovery.

"It's a self-care tool, designed to celebrate the human experience."
